nstance name. With the `max_peers` cap of 256 and typical multi-device counts of 2-3, this is fine in practice. But if multi-device counts grow or the peer limit increases, a `HashSet<String>` would be more appropriate. Not blocking, but worth a `// NOTE: Vec is fine for typical multi-device counts (2-3)` comment.\n\n**I3. Dynamic contact deduplication**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`, line 136\n\n```rust\ncontroller.contact_index.entry(routing_key).or_default().push(pubkey);\n```\n\nIf the same contact is added multiple times via `contact_rx` (e.g., user adds the same contact twice in the TUI), the same `PublicID` will appear multiple times in the candidates vector. This causes redundant verification work in `verify_peer_identity`. The initial contacts in `new()` have the same issue if duplicates are passed. Consider deduplicating (e.g., check `contains` before push), or document that duplicates are harmless.\n\n### Suggestions (nice to have)\n\n**S1. `refresh_all_peers` could parallelize verification**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/discovery/controller.rs`, lines 207-231\n\nCurrently, refresh re-verifies peers sequentially. With a 5-second per-request timeout and 256 max peers, worst case is ~21 minutes for a single refresh cycle. For typical deployments (a few peers) this is fine. If peer counts grow, consider `futures::stream::FuturesUnordered` for concurrent verification. Not blocking for now.\n\n**S2. Config `refresh_interval_secs` of 0 not validated**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/reme/apps/client/src/config.rs`, line 464\n\nA user setting `refresh_interval_secs = 0` would create a `tokio::time::interval(Duration::from_secs(0))`, which ticks immediately and continuously -- effectively a tight loop. Consider clamping to a minimum (e.g., 30 seconds) similar to how `max_peers` is clamped from 0 to 1.\n\n**S3. `register_stable` method appears unused**\n\nFile: `/home/leon0399/Projects/r