pped.\n\nHowever, a more likely explanation is simpler: **the `http_handle = handle.clone()` on line 503 and the original `handle` stored at line 748 are the only two live `Sender` holders.** If the HTTP server is not configured (`config.embedded_node.http_bind` is `None`), `http_handle` is never created, and the only clone is in `App.embedded_node_handle`.\n\nBut `App.embedded_node_handle` holds a live sender, so the channel should stay open. Unless... the `App` itself is dropped.\n\n### 5. What is actually happening in Bob's case\n\nThe most consistent explanation given the 1.5ms timing is: **`App::new()` is returning successfully, but the `App` object is being dropped very shortly after**. Or alternatively, the `App::new()` is failing after the node is spawned (returning `Err`), which drops the local `handle` variable.\n\nLook at the code flow again:\n\n```rust\nlet (node, handle, event_rx) = EmbeddedNode::new(mailbox_store);  // line 495\nlet join_handle = tokio::spawn(async move { node.run().await });   // line 496\n// ... many more lines of App::new() ...\n(Some(handle), Some(join_handle), Some(event_rx))                  // line 528\n```\n\nIf **any error is returned between lines 496 and 528**, the local binding `handle` gets dropped at the end of the `if` block. The spawned task's `requests` receiver will then see all senders gone, and `recv()` returns `None`, exiting the loop.\n\n**This is the bug.** The node is spawned before the handle is safely stored. If initialization fails partway through (e.g., the HTTP `bind_server` call at line 511–518 fails), the error is propagated upward, `handle` is dropped, and the node exits cleanly via the \"all senders dropped\" path — but the task and its resources (the `Arc<store>`) are already running in the background.\n\nWait — but Bob's log shows the HTTP server **does** continue to work. Let me re-examine.\n\n### 6. Re-reading: HTTP server works because it holds its own `Arc<store>` directly\n\nThis is the key archi