            "command": "gh issue create --title \"security: enforce public_id on direct peers to scope Tier 1 routing\" --body \"$(cat <<'EOF'\n## Problem\n\n`DirectPeerConfig.public_id` exists as `Option<String>` but bootstrap (`app.rs:622-645`) never calls `with_node_pubkey_opt()` when building targets. Because `TargetConfig::can_serve()` returns `true` when `node_pubkey` is `None`, any configured direct peer wins Tier 1 for **all** recipients regardless of which contacts it actually hosts.\n\n## Impact\n\nMisconfigured setups could route messages through the wrong direct peer. In practice, users configure direct peers per-contact, so current blast radius is limited.\n\n## Fix\n\nWire `DirectPeerConfig.public_id` through to `HttpTargetConfig::with_node_pubkey_opt()` in the bootstrap loop. This was explicitly deferred to Phase 6 (`ff27db4`) but should be revisited given the Tier 1 routing implications.\n\n## References\n\n- `apps/client/src/config.rs:503` — field definition\n- `apps/client/src/tui/app.rs:622-645` — bootstrap loop (missing wiring)\n- `crates/reme-transport/src/target.rs:582` — `can_serve()` optimistic fallback\nEOF\n)\" --label \"security\"",
