          "type": "assistant",
          "text": "Context is clear. The problem: `refresh_all_peers` verifies each peer sequentially with a 5s HTTP timeout. With many peers, this blocks the controller's `select!` loop. No visual questions here.\n\n## Two approaches\n\n**Approach A: `FuturesUnordered` with concurrency limit (Recommended)**\n\nSpawn all verification requests into a `FuturesUnordered`, process results as they complete. Since `verify_peer_identity` takes `&self` (immutable), the HTTP calls can run concurrently — only the result processing (mutating `peer_index`) needs to be sequential, which it already is via the `while let Some(...)` drain loop.\n\nThe tricky part: `verify_peer_identity` borrows `&self`, so we can't call it from inside a future while also mutating `self`. But we already clone the data upfront (`peers` vec). We can extract the HTTP client and run verification as a standalone function that takes the cloned data + an `Arc<reqwest::Client>` or just clones the client (it's cheaply cloneable in reqwest).\n\n- Pros: True concurrency, bounded by stream size (max_peers). With 256 peers at 5s timeout, worst case drops from ~21 minutes to ~5 seconds.\n- Cons: Slightly more complex than sequential. Need to handle the borrow issue.\n\n**Approach B: `tokio::spawn` per peer, collect via `JoinSet`**\n\nSpawn each verification as an independent tokio task, collect results via `JoinSet`. Each task owns its data (cloned name, url, identity, http_client).\n\n- Pros: Simple ownership model, no borrow issues.\n- Cons: Spawns up to 256 tasks — unnecessary overhead. No natural concurrency limit without adding a semaphore.\n\n**Recommendation: Approach A** — `FuturesUnordered` is the idiomatic tokio pattern for bounded concurrent I/O. The `reqwest::Client` is `Clone` (shares a connection pool internally), so we just clone it into each future. No need for `tokio::spawn` overhead.\n\nDoes this look right?",
